ST. LOUIS ENCEPHALITIS AND WEST NILE VIRUSES - USA (ARIZONA)
************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 21 Aug 2015
Source: KPHO [edited]
http://www.kpho.com/story/29848199/cdc-looking-at-outbreaks-of-2-mosquito-borne-diseases-in-az


In Maricopa County and across the state, 2 diseases -- West Nile [fever] virus and a little-known disease called St. Louis encephalitis -- are creating a health scare. The diseases are very similar in terms of symptoms, and both come from mosquitoes.

Infectious disease specialist Dr. Rebecca Sunenshine said it's unusual to have these 2 outbreaks at the same time. "We don't know exactly why they're happening at the same time," she said. "We've never seen that before."

So far, 46 cases of West Nile have been reported statewide, including 3 deaths. At the same time, 12 cases and one possible death from St. Louis encephalitis have been reported.

Health officials say it's extremely rare for both diseases to spread at the same time. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention is investigating to determine why it's happening.

"It may have something to do with the amount of rain we have had and the level of general water that is around for for mosquitoes to breed," Sunenshine.

The best way to protect yourself, according to Sunenshine, is to get rid of standing water around your home. Standing water is a perfect breeding ground for mosquitoes.

Experts also recommend that you wear clothes with long sleeves and long legs and use bug spray [repellant].

--
Communicated by:
Caitlin Rivers
Army Public Health Center
Black Hawk Rd, Gunpowder, MD 21010
