[These are the 1st cases of St. Louis encephalitis virus infection in Arizona that ProMED-mail has posted since 2003, which were also in Maricopa County (see ProMED-mail archive no. 20031015.2601). Biologically, it is not surprising that both West Nile and St. Louis encephalitis viruses are being transmitted in Arizona. Although no mosquito information is provided in the above report, the same species of _Culex_ mosquitoes is the vector of both. When West Nile virus 1st arrived in the USA in 1999, it was speculated that it would not become established in areas endemic for St. Louis encephalitis virus in the southern USA states, because they are antigenically very similar, being in the Japanese encephalitis virus group of flaviviruses, and wild bird hosts would already be immune. This hypothesis proved not to be the case, and the current outbreak in Arizona further illustrates that. Although the southwestern states of the USA are experiencing a drought, it is obviously not so severe in Arizona that vector mosquito populations are significantly decreased enough to prevent virus transmission. Since clinical disease represents a small fraction of individuals who are infected with either virus, there are almost certainly many more infected people than are reported above.

ProMED thanks Caitlin Rivers for submitting this report.

A map of the USA showing the location of Arizona can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3594184,106 and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3594184,207. - Mod.TY

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3594184,207.]
